%S A397092 0,1,1,6,20,86,341,1406,5697,23187,93847,379538,1530937,6167242
%N A397092 Number of free polyplets with n cells having exactly one corner-pinch contact (a pair of cells that touch only at a corner, both shared orthogonal-neighbor cells absent).
%C A397092 A polyplet is a set of unit cells on the square grid that is connected when cells may touch along an edge or at a corner (king-move, or 8-cell, connectivity), counted up to the symmetry group of the square; these are the polyplets enumerated by A030222.
%C A397092 a(n) is the number of such polyplets on n cells that have exactly one corner-pinch contact: a pair of cells that touch only at a corner, both of their shared orthogonal-neighbor cells being absent.
%C A397092 Every such polyplet is one of the polyplets counted by A030222, so a(n) is less than A030222(n) for all n >= 1; the first qualifying shape is the diagonal domino at n = 2.
%C A397092 By N. Madras's pattern theorem for lattice clusters (Annals of Combinatorics 3 (1999), 357-384), a corner-pinch contact is a local pattern occurring in the interior of large polyplets, so all but an exponentially small fraction of n-cell polyplets contain many of them; hence the proportion with exactly one tends to 0, and a(n)/A030222(n) tends to 0 as n grows.
%D A397092 N. Madras, A pattern theorem for lattice clusters, Annals of Combinatorics 3 (1999), 357-384.
%H A397092 Peter Exley, <a href="https://github.com/pexley-math/oeis-A397092">Paper and figures</a>, GitHub.
%Y A397092 Cf. A006770 (fixed polyplets touching at corners, the translation-distinct analog), A030222 (free polyplets, the base family that this sequence is a subcount of).
%K A397092 nonn,more
%O A397092 1,4
